ce:section.ce:para:
Herein, a smart point-of-care (SPOC) sensor, consisting of the fluorescent paper chip, 3D printed-accessories and smartphone, was developed for visual, swift and real-time/on-site AA detection in trace level (Scheme 1 in 
                        Supplementary Material
                     ). Fluorescent paper chip was made by printing silicon doped carbon dots (SiCDs)-Fe3+ as “ink” onto filter paper, in which SiCDs and Fe3+ act as FL signal and quencher, respectively. 3D printed-accessories, which were used to connect fluorescent paper chip with smartphone, could realize highly compatible with smartphones for adaptation in POC applications, and avoid the influence of ambient light or ultraviolet lamp excitation induced by the fringe effect when acquiring high-resolution image by smartphone. While smartphone containing image sensors could capture the FL color variation of SiCDs-Fe3+ induced by AA, whose content could be further digitized with self-designed APP program termed as “AA-Tester” based on gray value of images. The SPOC sensor was used to detect AA displayed excellent performance in practical samples, high performance liquid chromatography (HPLC) method was used to verify the method and obtained satisfactory recovery. There is no doubt that the SPOC sensor as a portable device will be favorable for rapid and real-time/on-site detecting AA outside controlled laboratory settings.

The SiCDs emitted blue FL at 425 nm, and its FL intensity was significantly quenched upon the addition of Fe3+ and then greatly recovered by AA, while the FL intensity of SiCDs had no change in the presence of the AA (Fig. 2
                        a). The FL quenching of fluorescent materials by metal ions generally originated from Förster resonant energy transfer (FRET), inner filter effect (IFE), and photoinduced electron transfer (PET). Herein, a series of experiments were conducted for further exploring the possible mechanism of FL quenching induced by Fe3+. As shown in Fig. 2b, the spectral overlapping between the absorbance of Fe3+ and the Em of SiCDs was negligible, which excluded the presence of FRET. Therefore, the detection of Fe3+ by SiCDs might be hypothesized to take place via IFE or PET. The UV–vis spectrum of Fe3+ partly overlapped with the Ex-spectrum of SiCDs, thus IFE might contribute to FL quenching. To further verify the assumption, additional studies were carried out. The IFE on Fe3+ and SiCDs was corrected and the correction factor (CF) of IFE (Fcorr/Fobsd
                        ) at each concentration of Fe3+ was summarized in Table S1. Approximately 20 % of the suppressed efficiency was from the IFE of Fe3+, signifying other quenching mechanism coexisting.
